@dean0x7d @jagerman 

First, thanks for your input.  I have a much better understanding of what is doing on now.

The TL;DR is that what I'm trying to do is unsupported, but it can be forced to work (see below).

A fundamental difficulty is that the one of the arguments (and individual) coming into the callback are constantly changing, meaning the whole idea of a Python process keeping references to them is simply absurd.

That said, I came up with a means of wrapping the type of function object that my library needs while also avoiding copies of objects, which I demonstrated to myself using simple cout lines from the const object constructors for the relevant types.  I am sure that this is unsafe, unsupported, fragile, and likely prone to break if any change to pybind11 ever occurs :).  I'm just going to copy/paste what worked in my app, rather than a simplified example:

```cpp
struct sink
{
    py::function f;
    sink(py::function f_) : f(std::move(f_)) {}
    //This fxn sig is what the external C++11 lib requires.  It is templated,
    //but the type constraints are well-defined:
    inline double
    operator()(const fwdpy11::diploid_t& dip, const fwdpy11::gcont_t& gametes,
               const fwdpy11::mcont_t& mutations) const
        /* The call operator returns a double never seen by Python.
         * It is recorded internally in the c++ library we're using.
         * The arguments are passed in by that lib, too.
         */
    {
                //steal pointers to objects
                //and avoid making copies
        auto d = py::cast(&dip, py::return_value_policy::automatic_reference);
        auto g
            = py::cast(&gametes, py::return_value_policy::automatic_reference);
        auto m = py::cast(&mutations,
                          py::return_value_policy::automatic_reference);
                //My compiler says a py::function cannot return a double,
                //so we get the rv...
        auto rv
            = f(*d.cast<fwdpy11::diploid_t*>(), *g.cast<fwdpy11::gcont_t*>(),
                *m.cast<fwdpy11::mcont_t*>());
                //...and cast it
        return rv.cast<double>();
    }
};
```

So, it works.  Yay!  But, aside from likely having side-effects that I'm unaware of, it is no faster than versions based on previous posts where I fool pybind11 into holding a reference to "gametes" and "mutations" while allowing the "diploid" to be copied at each call.  In other words, it is at least 10x slower than the native C++ code that it is wrapping.

I think I'm going to go to Plan B here, which is to define a base class with a pure virtual function returning a bound c++ callable.  That function returning the callable will __not__ be exposed to pybind11.  Rather, it will only be called from the pure C++ side, and thus these functions will have to be C++ only.  User's "custom" callables will inherit from this base class, and a const reference to the base will be passed in to the C++ functions.

I'm going to be happy with this: it is one thing that'll require C++ rather than tons of things requiring Cython.  It'll also allow "stateful" callables because std::bind will be allowed, which Cython cannot handle.

Again--thanks for the insight.  I'm going to start on Plan B this week, giving you until Monday or so to talk me out of it :).

